it cuts the revenue stream.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:29.120
And if the money doesn't come in
to pay for all these systems

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:31.700
to create these videos,
the videos are going to stop.

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:35.320
And there's nothing really keeping us
from stopping,

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:37.500
except that we think
that you still want the content.

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:39.100
So if you want it, we keep making it.

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:41.100
If you don't want it, we stop making it.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:42.020
So...

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.060
Where do we go from here?
What's the next step?

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:45.060
So yeah, let's jump into it.

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:46.700
Let's just get everything out
on the table.

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:49.700
Who's The King of Random?
Where did it come from? Where is it going?

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.600
So a little about myself,
I'm Grant Thompson.

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:54.780
I'm now known as The King of Random.
But way back in the day,

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:57.600
I was born in Calgary, Canada in Alberta.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:03:59.980
I grew up there, uh,
lived a few years in Calgary

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:02.900
and then we moved south of the city
to a little small town

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:05.200
that didn't even have street lights
or even a McDonalds.

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:07.900
And in that small town environment,
I started going to school,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.700
but I actually started having
a really hard time in school.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:12.800
I felt like I got bullied,
I got called names.

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:13.840
And a lot of people--

00:04:13.940 --> 00:04:17.100
Actually a couple people in particular,
went out of their way, every day,

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:20.200
to tell me what a loser,
and what a geek I was.

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:22.000
Um, the hard thing about that situation is

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:24.600
I didn't feel like I had any place
or group I belonged to.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:27.800
I wasn't a jock, I wasn't a nerd,
I wasn't anything.

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:30.400
I was by just myself,
which was really frustrating.

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.840
Uh, I would--
I wouldn't get picked on teams.

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:34.900
I'd always be the last one
to be picked on teams

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.300
even though I thought
I had some kind of athletic ability.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.060
There was just some stigma
of not wanting to be with me.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:41.800
So, I think that kinda hurt my feelings.

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:43.200
Now during that time of confusion,

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:46.820
my dad did something for me
that probably changed my life at age 14.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.700
He bought me a ticket
to go fly in an ultra light glider.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:53.000
And that was my first experience getting
into an airplane, flying above the city.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.100
What that did for me is
it changed my perspective,

00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:57.780
because this huge city
that was intimidating to me

00:04:57.780 --> 00:04:59.580
was now so small.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:02.000
Uh you know,
the people and the cars look like ants.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:03.700
And I could now really see in context

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:07.000
where that city fit in
to at least a bigger part of the world.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:08.400
That's when I knew
that I could make decisions

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:10.600
that would change me life,
I wasn't stuck in one place.

00:05:10.700 --> 00:05:11.800
So what I started doing was

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:14.800
I started going after everything
that made me feel better about myself.

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:15.800
Everything available.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:17.400
I went and got my drivers license,

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:18.900
'cause that made me
feel better about myself.

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:20.740
And then I got--
What's the next license after that?

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:22.800
I started driving buses, school buses,

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:25.400
and started doing trips
and tours for school kids.

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:27.300
Then I got my license
to drive motorcoaches,

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:30.740
the big 55 passenger buses,
and I started driving rock bands

00:05:30.740 --> 00:05:33.340
on tour around Canada,
which was very cool. [chuckles]

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:34.700
Then I took two years
of my life and I went

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.300
and served a mission in England,

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:38.600
where I supported myself
on money that I'd saved up

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:41.300
and I took two years
to go tell people about my beliefs.

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:43.900
And that was really strengthening,
because I was knocking on doors,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.900
talking to people,
sharing, uh, very personal information.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.900
And that taught me a lot of work ethic
and it got me into a lot of routines

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.300
that when I returned back,
I was ready to go.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:54.800
Now I knew that whatever I was gonna do 
was going to take a lot of money.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:57.900
And rather than going
to college or university at the time,

00:05:58.020 --> 00:05:59.300
I wanted to make sure...

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.420
I had a purpose for what
I was going to learn before I learned it.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:05.660
Um, I took a lot of time
to contemplate what I was interested in,

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:09.160
but I wasn't finding any colleges
or universities that met those needs

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:10.700
and I didn't really have a purpose to find.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:12.900
So while I was waiting
I got a job on the oil rigs

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.800
as a roughneck up in northern Canada,

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:18.660
where it was -60°C
and we worked outdoors 12 hours a day.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:20.660
- If you could believe that. So--
- Wow. Sounds cold.

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.600
Pretty crazy and we would
literally work 14 days straight

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:24.940
and then I have a couple days off.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.960
I actually lived in my car,
because I could save more money that way.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:29.500
They'd give us money for hotel and foods

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:32.400
and I actually just slept in my car
so I could save money faster.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:35.100
Long story short, I saved up enough money
to buy a small airplane.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.360
And I felt, at the time,
inspired to become an airline pilot.

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:41.800
So I figured the best way to do that,
was talk to people who had become pilots.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.560
And after listening
to a number of stories,

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:47.100
I decided to buy my own airplane,
build the flight time myself.

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.200
And that eventually carried me
over to Hawaii,

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:51.700
where I got a job as a cargo pilot
for about a year,

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:54.800
flying from Honolulu
to all the inter-islands around Hawaii.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:56.040
And once I got enough flight time,

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:58.400
I got hired by a commercial airliner
back in the mainlands.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:06:59.760
So I moved back to the mainland

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:02.700
and worked 11 years
as a commercial airline pilot.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:04.100
I bought my first house.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:05.500
That's where I met my wife.

00:07:05.900 --> 00:07:07.800
- And, uh, we--
- Where I bought my first house.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:09.700
She bought her house right beside me.

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:11.060
And we kept both of them,

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.980
and we fixed them up, we rented
them out and we kept buying houses,

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:14.880
fixing them up, renting them out,

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:17.300
until we had 11 houses,

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:18.680
fixed up and rented out.

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:20.280
So we got a business in real estate,

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:23.840
and the money that was coming in
was actually paying for our living expenses,

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:26.560
and so we started to have a little
bit more freedom with our time.

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:27.900
I was still working on the airlines,

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:29.540
but we built a business in real estate.

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:30.240
[Baby noise]

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:33.560
Now when the housing market
started to crash, we sold everything,

00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:36.080
and we put that money into investments,

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:37.920
and started living off of the interest.

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:41.340
And the cool thing about that scenario,
is now we had that time freedom,

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:42.800
that everybody wants to have.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:45.000
And it was a challenging time for me because...

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:48.140
now I had the opportunity to say, "What
have I always wanted to do with my life?"

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:53.180
And kind of live the dream of "if
money were not an object" or an issue,

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:54.440
what would you do with your time?

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:57.480
And I remember talking about this
with my wife, and what we ended up, uh,

00:07:57.480 --> 00:07:58.820
what I ended up coming with- was

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.500
I would love to just do things that
I love and make videos about it.

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.420
[chuckles] So...funny enough,

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:06.200
you know that's kind of what
got us into what we're doing, so...

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:09.400
If you could do anything you wanted
and money weren't a factor, what would you do?

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:11.460
For me, at the time, it was making videos.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:14.180
We've also had four kids and
we've now been married for 10 years,

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:15.620
but about 5 years ago,

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:18.760
we sold all of our houses we used
that money to invest in investments.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.080
And for the first time in my life,
I had a little bit of free time,

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:25.180
where I could scale back my hours at
the airlines and I had sometime to work,

00:08:25.180 --> 00:08:26.720
to tinker to figure out how things work.

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:29.960
Now, that was also around 2008-2009.

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:31.840
When everyone was talking about a Great Depression,

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:34.940
and falling back into the old ways where, you know,

00:08:35.060 --> 00:08:37.760
maybe there's gonna be an
apocalypse, people falling off the grid,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.260
you know banking systems crashing, who knows?

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.660
One thing I learned from reading books about history,

00:08:42.660 --> 00:08:44.600
is that some of the wealthiest people got their wealth,

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:46.320
during the biggest crisises,

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.500
and it all has to do with
opportunity meaning preparedness.

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.280
So, although I had a great career as an airline pilot,

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:54.340
I felt really insecure about my knowledge,

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:57.600
because I live in this time where we
have lights, we have electricity, we have...

00:08:57.960 --> 00:08:59.040
drinkable water,

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:00.560
we have toilets that we can just flush,

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:03.160
and I didn't know about how
any of those things worked.

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:04.540
Where does it all come from?

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:07.000
And if you were to go back 200 years in history,

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:09.240
when there were no electric light bulbs

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:11.320
and you could be the person to...

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:14.920
to revolutionize the economy to
bring light to people's homes,

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:17.500
would you be able to sufficiently
explain how that work,

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:18.480
do you know how it works enough,

00:09:18.820 --> 00:09:21.280
to where you could be that person
who invents that industry,

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:22.440
can you generate electricity?

00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:26.160
And for me, I thought, I... I...
can't explain how that works,

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:27.420
and yet we live in this...

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:30.900
this great time of technological
advantages where everything's available,

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:33.700
and i'ts on then internet, it's on
the Wikipedia, it's on YouTube.

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:34.680
So...

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:38.160
so what I decided to do was
devote my life to learning,

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:41.020
I wanted to learn how to weld,
I wanted to learn how to make circuit boards,

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:43.540
I wanted to learn how to be
Tony Stark, I wanted to learn...

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:45.900
how light bulbs work and be able to
explain how everything works around me.

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:49.260
The problem, I was finding is that as I was
going around to universities and colleges

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.120
looking for programs that taught this,

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.980
I couldn't find anything that would meet those needs.

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:58.180
So what I decided to do instead,
was try to a course of online study,

00:09:58.400 --> 00:09:59.540
the school of Grant Thompson,

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:02.560
pick something that I'm interested
and learned as much as I can about it,

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.440
until I can recreate it at
home using household materials.

00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:07.200
And in all my years in college,

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:12.140
I'd never seen anybody work as hard at
studying as Grant did during that time.

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:15.060
It's very... very focused study and it was very exciting.

00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:17.860
Because every morning I would jump
outta bed to go learn something new.

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:21.600
I was getting old televisions and hacking
them apart, I was ripping apart circuit boards,

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.440
do you remember when I was down there
de-sauteing all the components from...

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:27.720
circuit boards and then getting on Wikipedia
to find out what these things were,

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.520
you know, capacitors and triodes and
diodes...

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:32.320
- M-hmm.
- and transistor and resisters.

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:36.560
Yeah, our house became a factory
of all these gadgets taken apart.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:39.000
- [chuckles]
- Microwave-ovens and homemade rocket fuel...

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.820
that time we almost burned down the basement?

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:42.720
Yeah, of the house we were renting.

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:44.340
Yeah! [both laughs]

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:46.480
We actually used one of those
chemical fire extinguishers

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:48.500
and it took 2 days to clean up the mess.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:49.300
- Yeah!
- So...

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:50.860
those things happened.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.060
I saw, if there's going to be another Great Depression,

00:10:53.060 --> 00:10:54.780
the best thing that we could do, is get prepared

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:55.740
with knowledge.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.540
So I wanted to start studying how
things worked, I want to learn...

00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:01.980
how did our economy get to where it's at
and we lost all that for some reason,

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:04.900
could we rebuild it using common 
materials around the house,

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:07.080
basically. So thus was born
"The King of Random."

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:08.840
So to make a really long story short,

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:12.260
what ended up happening is, as I was
tinkering with things and making discoveries,

00:11:12.540 --> 00:11:13.780
I was learning about things that...

00:11:14.180 --> 00:11:15.520
- that aren't taught anywhere else.
- Mm-hmm.

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.720
Really, I was learning about how to
generate electricity, how to make motors,

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:20.280
how to play with high voltage

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:22.900
and, uh, how to make rocket fuel
and things of this nature.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:24.400
And every time I go to somebody's house

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:26.140
and just talk about these things I was learning,

00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:28.800
they would look at me like, "Who are you?
Where did you come from?"

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:31.320
Like, "Why do you know this stuff? That is so random!"

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:35.260
And one friend in particular, every time
I'd come over and he'd listen to this stuff,

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:38.600
he'd be like, "You know what?
You are like the king of random!"

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:41.740
Yeah, it seemed to be just a random different project

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:43.580
every time he would come visit us.

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:45.580
- Yeah.
- You know, it's periodic every few weeks

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:48.300
or whatever, but it was just always something different.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:51.080
- I mean, really intense.
- I mean, we're like dripping water through...

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:54.380
pop cans to generate electricity,
we were making Tesla coils,

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:57.180
we were making salt water capacitors,
a lot of really crazy stuff.

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:01.220
Yeah, what was that one that was like
creating rain and ozone and the smell of rain.

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:04.580
Yeah, I had a spark gap that would
actually make our house smell like ozone.

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:07.160
- Which is the smell that comes after a thunderstorm.
- I love that smell. [laughs]

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:09.560
- Yeah.
- That name kind of stuck "The King of Random,"

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:12.260
the king of random projects,
the king of random experiments, so...

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:15.600
about this time I was thinking if so many
people are finding value out of this,

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:18.160
what if I started a
YouTube channel to kind of give back?

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:22.040
I was learning so much information from
the internet from Wikipedia and from YouTube.

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:25.140
The problem I was having, is that
the format's people would upload in,

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:26.700
we're so difficult to follow,

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.160
15-20 minutes of somebody with their handy-cam

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:31.960
very shaky footage,
very hard to distill the information,

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:34.900
[baby noise] and half the time information
was wrong... that was a good pooper.

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:37.060
- Yeah! [laughs]
- Nice job bud, get out there, get out there.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:38.620
Our little man's doing a job right now.

00:12:38.620 --> 00:12:40.940
[laughs] Brief intermission,
we got to do a diaper change.

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:41.740
[laughs]

00:12:41.740 --> 00:12:44.540
So because I was coming into all this new
knowledge that wasn't really shared.

00:12:44.540 --> 00:12:47.460
I decided what I was going to do,
is become the man I was going to step up

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:50.820
and bring content to YouTube in a
very condensed, concise formula,

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:54.880
of how to do things that aren't usually
done and make discoveries, inventions,

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:58.680
and bring them to the world
in a package, where I've done all the prototyping

00:12:59.000 --> 00:12:59.980
and experimenting.

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:05.000
Also one of the gifts I've noticed,
as the wife of this incredible man,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.460
is that he's got a gift
to be able to take a lot of information

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:12.560
and distill it, if you will or condense it
down into the most important things

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:15.020
they're really easy to
understand and very shareable.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:18.220
And so that's kind of something
he's always been really good at...

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:20.620
- as well. 
- Thank you.
- Mmm-hm.

00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:23.720
And I had a lot of fun
with it, um, because...

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:26.220
it was really reverse engineering society

00:13:26.220 --> 00:13:28.560
and my goal was to be able to
know how to do everything...

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:32.140
that happens in society to be
able to purify water to keep, uh,

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:34.900
a roof over my family's head to be able to start fires

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:37.140
without matches.
What? Because if those aren't available,

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:41.180
um, I mean heat is one of the most
essential things you need access to you,

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:44.380
so you find a lot of my experiments have
to do with starting fire without matches.

00:13:44.380 --> 00:13:45.820
So this started my journey on YouTube

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:49.360
and you got to remember I'm working as
a full-time airline pilot and I have two kids...

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:53.120
at the same time. We're living a basement
apartment because we sold all of our properties

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:56.460
and we've got our money in investments
so that I can actually be taking the time...

00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:58.400
to do this
tinkering at home.

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:01.120
You know the other thing I that I remember,
we would have late-night conversations

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:04.360
about where YouTube could go because
even before we posted our first video,

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:07.440
we'd have conversations like this could lead to...

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:09.540
you'd becoming known,

00:14:09.540 --> 00:14:12.560
uh, you know it could lead to fame,
it could lead to going to television shows,

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:15.900
it could lead to you know a lot of big
opportunities, do we really want that?

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:19.500
Um, you know, because I'm kind of a private
person, I want to protect my family,

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:22.560
I want to give them a good life and so
coming out on the Internet [baby noise]

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.280
and sharing these things,

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:24.720
these things was very risky for me.

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:26.880
So when I started presenting my videos,

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:29.920
- you notice there are only my hands in the
videos you never saw my face.
- Mmm-hm.

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:31.760
It was very anonymous,

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:33.540
in some ways, and it came out of nowhere,

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:36.480
there's no history, there's no story,
you don't know anything about me

00:14:36.740 --> 00:14:38.540
or why I started posting those videos,

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:39.680
until today.

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:43.540
In contrary to what you might
think Grant is a very private person,

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:46.300
hence the reason he just had his
hands in a lot of the videos,

00:14:46.300 --> 00:14:48.860
because he didn't want to be seen
on camera and so as he's...

00:14:49.220 --> 00:14:50.740
grown and worked through those things

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:54.240
- you guys have also kind of seen
that evolution on "The King of Random."
- Mm-hmm.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.040
Yeah and YouTube itself has
been it's very own journey,

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.720
there's been a lot of things that happen
since we started posting on YouTube,

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:02.980
there's been a whole 'nother series of experiences.

